         <div type="translation">
            <p>[When the emperor Caesar Marcus Aurelius] Antoninus Augustus was consul for
                      the third time and the e[mperor Caesar Lucius Aurelius Vero was consul for the second
                      time], [present to sign (as witnesses)] in the curia of the basilica [Anniana] of Au[gustus
                      were --- As to] the matter, with everyone request[ing it --- regarding the
                      installation of the chariot for Silius Satrianus [--- what it pleased should happen
                      regarding this affair, regarding the affair [they thus decreed:</p>
            <p> --- since Silius Satria]nus, a most extraordinary man [---] the will [of?]
               the people [--- according to the agreement of all], a chariot from publ[ic] funds
               [---] and it was decreed [---] the chariot, from pu[blic] funds [---] </p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>Lines 1-2: The imperial dating formula is restorable based on the prosopography of the emperors.</p>
            <p>A good portion of the inscription is restorable because decurial decrees such as this one tend to be rather formulaic (cf. <ref target="http://www.edr-edr.it/edr_programmi/res_complex_comune.php?do=book&amp;id_nr=EDR158296" type="external">EDR158296</ref> and <ref target="http://www.edr-edr.it/edr_programmi/res_complex_comune.php?do=book&amp;id_nr=EDR158673" type="external">EDR158673</ref>). </p>
            <p>
               <seg type="material">Proconnesian(?) coarse-grained
                      gray marble</seg> (Tuck).</p>
            <p>Probably a document detailing the dedication of chariot to one Silius Satrianus.</p>
         </div>
